definition.value: An endpoint defined an effect seen in animals at a particular dosage, typically defined as a ratio of treatment to animal mass (e.g., mg/kg).
The median lethal dose is the dose required to kill (produce lethality) in 50% of tested population.
An endpoint derived from calculus-based analysis of graphical measures.
The maximal concentration of a drug achieved following administration (maximum point of a concentration-time curve).
It is the area under the drug concentration-time curve (AUC) following a single dose or at steady state, and is expressed as weight*time/volume.

Slope is described as the ratio of the change in y-axis divided by the change in x-axis between two points on a line or a curve.

m= y2-y1 / x2-x1
Endpoint values derived from an exponential growth curve, such as in a PCR reaction.

Crossing point- In an exponential amplification curve (i.e., qPCR amplification) the value in number of amplification cycles at which the signal enters log phase, as determined by the maximal second derivative of the curve.
Quantificatoin cycle; general term, whether defined by Cp or Ct, for the value of interest determined from an exponential amplification curve (such as number of cycles in a PCR reaction).
Crossing threshold; in an exponential amplification curve (i.e., qPCR amplification) the value in number of amplification cycles at which the signal crosses a defined threshold.
Endpoint values determined by a statistical measurement of the signal relative to the populations of signals observed.
The number of median absolute deviations outside the median of control or compound wells.

An endpoint defined by a set of measurements from a multiparametric assay.  The set of measurements may be aggregated to an overall profile score, weighting each measurment in the profile relative to a desired outcome.
The effective concentration of an inhibitor, which produces 90% of the maximum possible response for that inhibitor.
It is 50% lethal concentration (the concentration that kills 50% of treated cells).
The lowest concentration of an inhibitor (antimicrobial agent) required to inhibit the growth of a microorganism.

It is a measure of the amount of radioligand that binds to its receptor in a competitive binding assay. It is the ratio of the bound to the total bound, where bound refers to the reading obtained from a binding reaction involving radioligand, receptor and a cold competitor ligand, while total bound is the reading obtained in the absence of any added competitor.

In a purification assay, percent recovery is the ratio of mass of the entity obtained after the affinity purification to the mass of the unpurified entity originally added in the assay, multiplied by 100.
